I was reading an interview w/ a German professor, who was writing on the topic of eroticism in the works of Baron Jules Evola, where he mentioned Paul Valéry's Paradox: the skin is the most "superficial" organ (literally), but in love it is experienced as the most "profound" one.

In his books on "Eros and the Mysteries of Love", Dr. Evola cites a definition of romantic love as "the contact between two skins and the exchange of two fantasies.", thus the old expression "to fancy someone" ("fancy", etymologically stemming from "fantasize", not as "fashion").

Just as Paracelsus said that: "The liver is in all organs, but has its head in what we call the liver.", or Guenon says the heart spoken of in spiritual text is not too-literally the physical heart, but it is still "analogous", related, so this too applies for skin's erogenicity.
